    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-08-27T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-08-27T09:00:00-05:00" n="712"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d712">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">660f.116Auto/27: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Czechoslovakia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Einstein</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Prague</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-08-27T15:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 27, 1928—3 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received 3:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>67. Your 39, August 14, 7 p.m. Note from Foreign Office with trade statistics
                    reiterates contention that Czechoslovakia although obliged to grant only
                    contingent equal to treaty provisions has exceeded this by issuing 1300 licenses
                    this year. It states that the workers organizations fear the consequences of
                    removing restriction on imports particularly as metal industries have been
                    affected by foreign customs barriers and the skilled labor from these finds
                    employment in motors. Protection is compared to the emigration quota in America.
                    Further arguments are presented showing the balance of trade favors the United
                    States and mention is made of prohibition as preventing various Czechoslovak
                    exports. To show its good will, the importation of one hundred and eighty cars
                    is authorized credited against next year’s contingent. Copy of note forwarded by
                    next pouch.<note n="50" xml:id="d712fn50">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>[Paraphrase.] As I have already emphasized the points given in Department’s 39
                    and made vigorous representations, for the present I am of opinion that nothing
                    further can be accomplished through ordinary argument, though American
                    automobiles may be imported still in dribblets. Any increased admission of
                    American motors must depend on steps being taken in Washington. [End
                    paraphrase.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Einstein</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
